## Context
The headline numbers — the $100bn pledge and the Baku NCQG — are where the
aggregate does its distributive work. Reviewer 2 asked that the provenance and the
scale be documented precisely rather than gestured at. The Vannes notes add the
Baku 1.3T/0.3T gap and the Southern reading of the aggregate. Tracker: 0141.

## Relevant passages
- `content/manuscript.qmd` §2.3 / §3 — $100bn provenance ("not derived from any
  economic model"); Copenhagen context; the "$100bn vs US defense" scale
  provocation; the Baku NCQG paragraph; p16 UN Advisory Group composition.
- `docs/notes-vannes-2026-07.md` §4–5.

## Actions
1. Document the $100bn provenance precisely: Copenhagen Accord, who set it, that it
   was not derived from a model.
2. Address scale: the concrete comparator is the ~$1.01T US defense budget (Trump's
   >$1T ask, FY26) — cite the figure, keep the provocation measured.
3. Muscle the Baku paragraph with the gap: developing countries asked $1,300bn/yr;
   the NCQG core target is $300bn; the 1.3T survives only as the aspirational
   "Baku to Belem Roadmap", outside the obligation.
4. Add the Southern reading (Dupont): countries decompose the aggregate —
   "combien je vaux" — using it to value countries, not only to verify donors.
5. UN Advisory Group composition (p16): finance ministers, economists, central
   bankers, no climate scientists — reflect on whether it matters.

## Test (prose ratchet)
- Negative guard only; any $-figure cited must be traceable to an archived source
  (see `feedback_manuscript_number_provenance`).

## Exit criteria
- [ ] $100bn provenance + scale + Baku gap + Southern reading + Advisory Group all revised
- [ ] Cover-letter traceability rows updated with §ref + commit SHA
- [ ] Prose in the author's voice per `docs/style-anchor-v205.md`; `make check-fast` green
